Background and Overview

Santander Bank

Santander Bank is a wholly owned subsidiary of the Spanish Santander Group. As part of its operation mission, Santander offers services to help people and businesses prosper. They work tirelessly to help their customers understand their financial health and identify which products and services might help them achieve their monetary goals.

In this presentation, I will develop several models in the effort to understand specific customer behavior. We will be using the data set Santander Customer Transaction Prediction to help classify a target variable that predicts the answer to questions such as: is the customer satisfied with a product or service? Will a customer buy a particular product? Or can a customer pay this loan?

Dataset

We will be using the Santander Customer Transaction Prediction dataset:

1. The dataset is directly provided by the Santander the Bank with a real-life structure.

2. The features have been renamed for security and discretionary purposes. File size is 1.01 GB.

3. The data contains 201 features, 1 target value and 200,000 observations.

4. The data was overall clean and only needed to drop 1 features and Some NAs for modeling.

### Matrix Partition for Lasso and Xgboost
x=model.matrix(target~.,SantanderDF)[,-1]
y=SantanderDF$target 

set.seed(5082)
train = sample(1:nrow(x), nrow(x)*3/4)
test = (-train)
x.train = x[train,]
x.test = x[test, ]
y.train = y[train]
y.test =y[test]

Lasso

Lasso is a type of regression analysis that performs both variable selection and regularization to enhance prediction accuracy. It is a powerful method that performs two main tasks: regularization and feature selection.

During the feature selection process the variables that still have a non-zero coefficient after the shrinking process are selected to be part of the model.

The goal of this process is to minimize the prediction error.

There are many advantages in using lasso:

1. Very good prediction accuracy

2. Easily interpreted model

3. Overfitting is reduced

There are also some disadvantages to lasso:

1. The model isnt very stable, so the selected features might change each time it is run

2. The model selection result is not intuitive to interpret

3. Doesnt perform well with highly correlated features

Note: None of the public notebooks used feature selection to increase their model accuracy.

library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.1
# Create a grid of 50 lambda values to tune
grid = 10^seq(10,-2,length=50)

set.seed(5082)
# Train a Lasso model using the training dataset and the lambda grid created above
mod.lasso <- glmnet(x.train,  
                    y.train, 
                    alpha=1, 
                    lambda=grid,
                    standardize = TRUE,
                    family="binomial",
                    type.measure = "mse")

# Evaluate training model performance using cross-validation
cv.out.class <- cv.glmnet(x.train,  
                          y.train, 
                          alpha=1, 
                          lambda=grid,
                          nfolds = 10,
                          family="binomial")

# Display the best cross-validated lambda value:
(bestlam <- cv.out.class$lambda.min)
## [1] 0.01
#cross validation can also be used to select lambda.
plot(cv.out.class)

# Using the best lambda and the trained model, 
lasso.pred.class <- predict(mod.lasso, 
                            s=bestlam, 
                            newx=x.test, 
                            type="class")

Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression is a type of regression that is typically used for classification and it is simple to implement.

Pros:

1. Very efficient to train

2. Good accuracy for datasets that are linearly separable

3. Doesnt overfit the data

Cons:

1. Cant be used with non-linear data

2. Doesnt work well with multi-collinearity

Logistic regression works well, but there are some problems with this model: 1. Feature selection is not very efficient with 200 features

2. Assumptions check

  - Multicolinearity
  - Linearity
  - Heteroscadesticity

3. Methods used on Kaggle:

Generate correlation table, drop highly correlated columns that have a correlation larger than 0.95 https://www.kaggle.com/ashu11081992/basic-logistic-regression

  • Ignored the problem:https://www.kaggle.com/nurzhann173/logistic-regression
  • Both Problematic

4. Using features selected by Lasso, we built logistic regression model. The model yielded a high accuracy rate of 0.91. However, the model is not stable. The coefficients and p-values of variables varies from time to time with seed set

Xgboost

XGBoost (Extreme Gradient Boosting) is an optimized distributed gradient boosting library. Yes, it uses gradient boosting (GBM) framework at core. Yet, does better than GBM framework alone

Lets look at what makes it so good:

1. Parallel Computing: It is enabled with parallel processing (using OpenMP); i.e., when you run xgboost, by default, it would use all the cores of your laptop/machine

2. Regularization: I believe this is the biggest advantage of xgboost. GBM has no provision for regularization. Regularization is a technique used to avoid overfitting in linear and tree-based models.

3. Enabled Cross Validation: In R, we usually use external packages such as caret and mlr to obtain CV results. But, xgboost is enabled with internal CV function (well see below)

4. Missing Values: XGBoost is designed to handle missing values internally. The missing values are treated in such a manner that if there exists any trend in missing values, it is captured by the model

5. Flexibility: In addition to regression, classification, and ranking problems, it supports user-defined objective functions also. An objective function is used to measure the performance of the model given a certain set of parameters. Furthermore, it supports user defined evaluation metrics as well

6. Availability: Currently, it is available for programming languages such as R, Python, Java, Julia, and Scala

7. Save and Reload: XGBoost gives us a feature to save our data matrix and model and reload it later. Suppose, we have a large data set, we can simply save the model and use it in future instead of wasting time redoing the computation

8. Tree Pruning: Unlike GBM, where tree pruning stops once a negative loss is encountered, XGBoost grows the tree upto max_depth and then prune backward until the improvement in loss function is below a threshold

Interpretation:

  • From looking at the training and validation errors, it looks as though the model may have performed quite well in predicting whether or not customers satisfaction for this particular validation set, but there is no guarantee that it will do so on other datasets.

Comparisson to Public Notebook:

When comparing our xgboost, the models posted on Kaggle, our team did a better job of performing cross validation and ensuring that the parameters used in Xgboost were optimal. Many models, such as the one found here (https://www.kaggle.com/ho1zlar/azamatmidterm), only tune the model and do not perform cross validation. This cross validation was essential in setting the best possible parameters such as learning rate, minimizing the RMSE and maximizing the AUC.

Also, we calculated the following ratios:

Recall(or sensitivity): for this competition, is by far a more important ratio since it is important to even indentify some customers who will not be purchassing certain product or services rather than leaving an interested customer out.
Recall = 1.00000

Precision: is how sure you are of your true positives and if we want to cover all true negatives. In our model, false positives are intolerable, so this ratio is not as important as recall. Precision = 0.898718

F1: Conveys the balance between the precision and the recall. F1 = 0.9465181

ROC: Shows the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds. Lowering the classification threshold classifies more items as 0, thus increasing both False Positives and True Positives.

Machine Learning Reproducibility Checklist

1. In our presentation, we explicitly described the three models (lasso, logistic, and XGBoost)

2. During logistic regression, because of the number of features used we had to do feature elimination to be able to satisfy the assumptions (linearity, multicollinearity, and heteroscadesticity) - The public notebooks that we found using logistic regression didnt check assumptions appropriately. Without considering the assumptions, such as linearity and multicollinearity, the model could be problematic even with its high accuracy.

3. When trying to run an SVM model, we faced an issue with the sample size and space and were not able to create a working model. Having a range of costs and gamma in order to tune our model introduced even more complexity

4. All theoretical claims made were substantiated with code

For all datasets used:

1. Santander Customer Transaction Prediction included 202 features and 200,000 observations. The id was excluded from the features because it didnt provide any relevant data and there were no NAs

2. The data was split into train and test sets with the train set having 75% of the observations

3. To preprocess this data, we scaled and normalized our observations

4. https://www.kaggle.com/c/santander-customer-transaction-prediction/data?select=train.csv
